/-!
# Second Moment Method for Large Divisors (L2 Deviation Synthesis)

This file implements the second-moment/Cauchy-Schwarz bounds needed to control the
large-divisor tail in the error term of the Granville–Kurlberg theorem (GK08 §3.1).

## Strategy

For each nonempty subset `T ⊆ primeFactors(q)`, we bound the per-T
inclusion-exclusion contribution by `C · ∏_{p ∈ T} combinedEulerWeight`. The
proof decomposes into two cases:

### Case 1: All primes in T are large (p > B_max)

The box lattice points give injective tuples mod p (by `fin_cons_castHom_injective`),
so the `WellDistributed` first component yields `|N_p(h) − μ_p| ≤ cEW_p · μ_p`
pointwise. Summing over h and absorbing the prefactor gives the bound directly.

### Case 2: T contains at least one small prime

The key insight is the **mean-zero cancellation**: for each prime p,
`∑_{r_p} (N_p(r_p) − μ_p) = 0` (the local count has exact mean μ_p over all
residue classes). By CRT, the product `∑_r ∏_T g_p(r_p) = 0` over complete
residue systems. The lattice-point sum differs from zero only by a boundary
error controlled by `C_lp`.

## Main Results

* `deviation_L1_le_L2` — Cauchy-Schwarz for finite sums.
* `mean_zero_local_deviation` — Mean-zero property of local deviations.
* `all_large_per_T_bound` — Per-T bound when all primes in T are large.
* `per_T_deviation_le_combinedEulerWeight` — The complete per-T bound.
-/

